MatrixOS sensors and computer vision algorithms provide data which can be filtered between the  init , which can be regarded as the data source, and the  then , which can be regarded as the data receiver. Between the two, we can use chaining methods to easily filter what data is received.  // filtering in a simple application
matrix.init('temperature')
.above(80)
.then(function(data){
  // see CrossTalk documentation for more information about matrix.emit
  matrix.emit('ac-control', 'turnOn');
});  Filtering decides whether or not a data point is passed to the  then() , it does not change the data in any way.

has()  is used to refine a data source by additional criteria and keys.  // for simple sensors
matrix.init('temperature').has('value')
// equivalent to
matrix.init('temperature').has()

// for complex sensors
matrix.init('gyro').has('x')

// for detections
matrix.init('face').has('age')

